Controversies[edit]
Abu Ghraib[edit]
On June 9, 2004, a group of Iraqis sued CACI International and Titan Corporation (now Engility)[40] in U.S. federal court. The plaintiffs, former detainees, allege that the companies directed and participated in torture, war crimes, crimes against humanity, sexual assault, as well as cruel, inhuman and degrading treatment at Abu Ghraib prison. The U.S. Government had hired CACI and Titan to provide interrogation and translation services at military prisons in Iraq.[41]
In 2009, the U.S. Court of Appeals for the D.C. Circuit ruled in CACI’s favor in the lawsuit and ordered its dismissal.[42] The U.S. Supreme Court then declined to review that decision.[43] 
CACI employee Steven Stephanowicz and several military officers were investigated in the Taguba inquiry. A subsequent investigation of military intelligence operations at Abu Ghraib found that "contractors were involved in 36 percent of the [Abu Ghraib] proven incidents" and identified 6 employees as "individually culpable", but none have been prosecuted.[44]
CACI Response[edit]
According to CACI's website, "the company provided a range of Information Technology (IT) and intelligence services in Iraq. These services included intelligence analysis, background investigations, screenings, interrogation, property management and recordkeeping, and installation of computer systems, software and hardware. Only a small portion of these employees worked as interrogators." The company states that "no CACI employee or former employee has been indicted for any misconduct in connection with this work, and no CACI employee or former employee appears in any of the photos released from Abu Ghraib." CACI also adds that they "are no longer providing interrogation services in Iraq", which concluded in the early fall of 2005 upon the conclusion of a contract with the Department of the Army.
CACI also adds "nonetheless, we do not condone, tolerate or endorse any illegal behavior by our employees in any circumstance or at any time. We will act forcefully if the evidence shows that any of our employees acted improperly, but we will not rush to judgment on the basis of speculation, innuendo, partial reports or incomplete investigations."
CACI also claims on their website that U.S. Government reports generally "concluded that civilian interrogators performed their duties in an appropriate fashion and made a major contribution to the U.S. mission in Iraq." CACI further claims a March 2005 report by U.S. Navy Inspector General and Vice Admiral Albert T. Church shows that despite the publicity surrounding Abu Ghraib, "we found very few instances of abuse involving contractors."[45]
CACI Chairman of the Board Dr. Jack London[46] defended the company with a book: CACI: Our Good Name.
Lawsuit[edit]
In May 2008, four former Abu Ghraib prison detainees brought separate lawsuits in four U.S. courts against CACI and L-3 Communications as well as against three civilians. One of these former inmates, Emad al-Janabi, sued L-3 and CACI for allowing their employees to abuse him physically and mentally at the prison.[47] In a statement released on its website, CACI has stated that these lawsuits are "baseless" and they "reject emphatically this latest plaintiff's allegations and claims" calling on "numerous and thorough government investigations" in these allegations.[48]
On March 19, 2009, US District Judge Gerald Bruce Lee rejected claims by CACI that it could not be sued because its interrogators were performing duties prescribed by the contract with the U.S. government. CACI responded that it vowed to "pursue all of its legal alternatives to defend itself and vindicate the company's good name" and that "From day one, CACI has rejected the outrageous allegations against the company in this lawsuit and continues to do so."[49]
On September 11, 2009, the U.S. Court of Appeals ruled that CACI did in fact fall under U.S. military chain of command and thus had government contractor immunity.[50] Subsequently, the U.S. Court of Appeals for the Fourth Circuit reheard the appeal, with all active judges participating, and in an 11-3 decision held that the appeal was premature.[51] The action was remanded to the district court for further proceedings.[51]
On remand, the plaintiffs were able to conduct full discovery into their claims. After that discovery, the plaintiffs had not identified any evidence that showed that anyone affiliated with CACI had any contact with the plaintiffs. In June 2013, Judge Lee dismissed the suit due to lack of jurisdiction.[52]
On appeal, the U.S. Court of Appeals for the 4th Circuit found that the lower court had erred in dismissing the suit in June 2013, as it lacked jurisdiction to hear the case because the alleged incidents occurred overseas.[53] The appellate court vacated the district court’s decision and remanded the case for a determination of whether plaintiffs’ claims were barred by the political question doctrine.[54] 
In June 2015, the U.S. District Court again dismissed the case against CACI, holding that CACI’s actions were controlled by the U.S. military and that assessing torture and war crimes claims would require impermissible review of the U.S. military’s judgment, and thus the issues in the case present a “political question” that the judiciary cannot appropriately answer.[55] 
In October 2016, the U.S. Court of Appeals for the Fourth Circuit reinstated the case.[56] The court concluded that CACI’s actions are protected from judicial review under the political question doctrine if they were lawful when committed and occurred under actual control of the U.S. military or involved sensitive military judgments.[56] The court remanded the case to the U.S. District Court to re-examine its subject matter jurisdiction as outlined in the U.S. Court of Appeal’s opinion.[56]
